Good, this screenshot helps ğŸ‘
You are very close. The UI logic is now correct; the remaining issue is a data-shape bug, not an Angular or PrimeNG issue.

â¸»

ğŸ”´ EXACT ERROR (from console)

ERROR TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'trim')
at PIPFormComponent.formatEmployeeName

â— What this means

formatEmployeeName() is being called with undefined, so this line fails:

parts[1].trim()

That means for at least one row, NAME is null / undefined / empty.

â¸»

ğŸ” WHY THIS IS HAPPENING (VERY IMPORTANT)

From your SharePoint screenshot:

Row	MANAGER1UID	NAME
1	h59604	âœ” Present
2	a73693	âœ” Present
3	h59604	âœ” Present

But your SharePoint REST response actually contains rows like:

{ __metadata: {...}, MANAGER1UID: 'h59604' }

â¡ï¸ Some rows do NOT include NAME or Email at all
â¡ï¸ Thatâ€™s why e.NAME becomes undefined

This is 100% expected behavior in SharePoint when:
	â€¢	Column is empty
	â€¢	Column is not included in $select
	â€¢	Column name mismatch (case-sensitive)

â¸»

âœ… THE REAL FIX (SAFE + CORRECT)

ğŸ”§ Fix 1: Make formatEmployeeName bullet-proof

Replace your function with THIS EXACT VERSION ğŸ‘‡

formatEmployeeName(raw: any): string {
  if (!raw || typeof raw !== 'string') {
    return '';
  }

  const parts = raw.split(',');
  if (parts.length === 2) {
    return `${parts[1]?.trim() ?? ''} ${parts[0]?.trim() ?? ''}`.trim();
  }

  return raw.trim();
}

This alone will stop the runtime crash.

â¸»

ğŸ”§ Fix 2: Guard while mapping employees (VERY IMPORTANT)

Replace ONLY this part in loadEmployeesUnderManager ğŸ‘‡

âŒ OLD (causing crash)

this.employeeOptions = rows
  .filter(r => r.MANAGER1UID === managerUid)
  .map(r => ({
    uid: r.EmpUID,
    name: this.formatEmployeeName(r.NAME),
    email: r.Email ?? ''
  }));

âœ… NEW (SAFE & CORRECT)

this.employeeOptions = rows
  .filter(r => r.MANAGER1UID === managerUid && r.EmpUID)
  .map(r => ({
    uid: r.EmpUID,
    name: this.formatEmployeeName(r.NAME ?? ''),
    email: r.Email ?? ''
  }));


â¸»

ğŸ” WHY YOU SAW THIS IN CONSOLE

Employees under manager: [{â€¦}]
Manager rows from SharePoint: (3) [â€¦]
Matched Manager Row: { MANAGER1UID: 'h59604' }

âœ” Filtering is working
âœ” Manager match is correct
âŒ One employee row has missing NAME

â¸»

âœ… WHY DROPDOWN SHOWS â€œNo results foundâ€

PrimeNG shows that when:
	â€¢	options.length === 0
	â€¢	OR rendering crashed before population

Because the error occurred during .map(), Angular never reached assignment.

After this fix:
âœ” Dropdown WILL show 2 employees under h59604

â¸»

ğŸ§  VERY IMPORTANT CLARITY (Your Doubt)

â€œManager h59604 is assigned to 2 employees, but matched manager shows only oneâ€

That is correct behavior:
	â€¢	Matched manager â†’ single row
	â€¢	Employees under manager â†’ multiple rows

They are different concepts, and your logs confirm logic is correct.

