Great! Since youâ€™re not using SCSS, and want to continue using regular .css, hereâ€™s how to fix the AG Grid v33 error using .css only, without migrating to SCSS.

â¸»

âœ… Fix for AG Grid v33+ using .css

âœ… Step 1: Use the new Theming CSS file

Instead of importing ag-theme-alpine.css (legacy), use the new path:

// âœ… Use new Theming API CSS file
import 'ag-grid-community/styles/ag-grid.css';
import 'ag-grid-community/styles/themes/ag-theme-alpine.css'; // âœ… updated path

âš ï¸ This matches AG Gridâ€™s v33+ theme structure.

â¸»

âœ… Step 2: Use theme correctly in HTML

In your app.component.html, wrap your grid with the correct theme class:

<div class="ag-theme-alpine" style="height: 400px; width: 600px;">
  <ag-grid-angular
    [rowData]="rowData"
    [columnDefs]="columnDefs"
    [defaultColDef]="defaultColDef"
    [animateRows]="true"
    [rowSelection]="{ type: 'single' }" <!-- âœ… new format -->
    (gridReady)="onGridReady($event)">
  </ag-grid-angular>
</div>


â¸»

âœ… Step 3: Add defaultColDef and onGridReady (optional but good practice)

In your app.component.ts:

defaultColDef: ColDef = {
  sortable: true,
  filter: true,
  resizable: true
};

onGridReady(params: GridReadyEvent) {
  params.api.sizeColumnsToFit();
}

Donâ€™t forget to import:

import { GridReadyEvent } from 'ag-grid-community';


â¸»

